perfect combs,\n1 and other equipment cheap,\n\u2014Geo. Foote. Grand Rapids, O.\nFOR SALE\u2014 Timothy hay, 3 1-2\nmi. south of G. Rapids. D. Stocker\nFOR SALE\u2014 Snails for fish aquar\nium, have 21 little ones. Mrs. C. F.\nKendall.\nFOR SALE\u2014House ana two lots\nwith garage and lots of fruit.\nInquire at News office.\nFOR SALE\u2014House and lot on\nMain street, inquire at News office.\nFOR SALE\u2014 The August Kosch\nhome. 5 acres of land located 3 1-2\nmiles north of Grand Rapids on a\ngood stone road. 2 room house,\n14x20, Chicken house, 12x40 and\nother out buildings. Inquire at the\nWatervllle State Savings Bank Co.\n2t\u2014c. 4111\nLadies and children\u2019s Fast Col\nored Print Dresses, Values to $1.35,\nonly 98c. The Bell Store.\nWANTED TO SELL\u2014Woodbnrn\u2019s\nSeed Corn, 1928 corn, germination\n90 to 98 per cent, $4.00. Rack\ndried 192\u00b0 corn, germination 80\nto 90 per cent, $3.00 per bushel,\nshelled and graded; all corn growr\\\nfrom certified seed. C. W- Mast.\nWaterville, O. 4t Apr. 25\nWANTED\u2014To employ woman at'\nRapids Hotel. Must be good cook.\nApply in person. Mrs. Lulu San\nders, Grand Rapids, O. 2t Apr25\nDISTRIBUTOR WANTED.\u2014 Large\nmanufacturer of nationally known\nproduct, wants capable party to*\ntake exclusive sales; retail and\nwholesale trade in Grand Rapids\nterritory. Steady, repeat orders. No\ncompetition. This business should\nnet party between $10,000.00 and\n$12,000.00 per year. Party must be\nfinancially responsible to carry\n$2,000.00 to $5,000.00 worth of\nmerchandise. Official will be in\nGrand Rapids shortly. Write Man\nufacturer, 767 Milwaukee Avenue.\nChicago, give phone for interview.\nCounty Court News\nAuditor Appoints Assessors\nCounty Auditor, A. O. Cummings\nWednesday apointed the complete\nlist of deputy tax assessors who he\nhas appointed for this year. Per\nsonal tax blanks were mailed last\nMonday and they must be filled\nout, sworn to before one of the as\nsessors or at the Auditors office\nand filed by May 1 to obtain the\n$100 exemption.\nThe assessors for the various\ncorporations are as follows:\nBairdstown\u2014Louise Ickes.\nBloomdale\u2014J. L. Van Eman.\nBowling Green\u2014A'. L. Sloan.\nBradner\u2014Daniel Stahl.\nCustar\u2014E. L. Huffine.\nCygnet\u2014Louise Ickes.\nGrand Rapids\u2014James H. Burweil.\nHaskins\u2014Grace Garrett.\nHoytville\u2014Jesse Ferguson,\njerry City\u2014Louise Ickes.\nMillbnry\u2014Phillip Diefenthaler.\nMiltou Center\u2014I. E- Rummell.\nNorth Baltimore\u2014E. S- Morehead.\nPemberville\u2014S. C. Speck.\nPerrysburg\u2014Pearl Lyons.\nPortage\u2014W. A. Esterly.\nRislngsun\u2014S. S. Shaw.\nRossford (sell dist)\u2014Oscar Holst.\nTontogany\u2014Oscar Sears.\nWalbridge\u2014Alonzd Tyler.\nWayne\u2014E. E. Frisbie.\nWest Milgrove\u2014J. E. Wirt.\nWeston\u2014Charles Seitz.\nThe assessors for the twenty\ntownships are:\nBloom \u2014Louise Ickes\nCenter \u2014Charles J. Whitmer.\nFreedom '\u2014Carl Hoodlebrink.\nGrand Rapids \u2014E. E. Ellsworth.\nHpnry \u2014J .H. Apple.\nJackson \u2014John H. Hanna.\nn\nSpring Time Brings House\nCleaning Time\nWhile you\u2019re cleaning and\nbeautifying your home,\nwhy not add a new living\nroom suite, to make it\nmore beautiful?- It will\ncap the climax.\nFred Gill\nFurniture Undertaking\nGRAND RAPIDS, OHIO\nLake \u2014Frank Waggoner.\nLiberty \u2014Milton \u201cSweet.\nMiddleton \u2014east\u2014I. E. Ward.\nM.ddle.on,. west\u2014F. J. Cauer.\nMilton \u2014Emory Bnrson. U\nMontgomery \u2014E. E. Frisbie.\nPerry -\u2014J. E. Wirt.\nPtrrysbnrg \u2014T. H. Tinney.\nPlain \u2014George B. Chapman.\nPortage \u2014W. T. Easterly.\nRoss \u2014Howard Vilters.\nTroy \u2014Frank Joseph.\nWashington \u2014Cs.-ar Sears.\nWebster \u2014J. I). Philo.\nWeston \u2014William Jimison.\nProbate Court\nPetition filed 'to determine inher\nitance tax in estate of Albert Min\nnick; no tax due.\nWill of Otto Hamen filed and\napplication to probate.\nFinal account filed by William\nHanely, executor of will of Samuel\nHanely.\nFinal account filed by J. H. Ap\nple, administrator of estate of\nLouis A. Neier.\nOrder of private sale of real es\ntate \"issued by E K. Solether, ad\nministrator of estate of William\nSchneider.\nWill of James F. Sanders admit\nted to probate: Harry. S. Payson\napointed executor.\nE. M. Fries appointed adminis\ntrator of estate of Hugh Stewart.\nWill of Gertrude Clark filed and\napplication to prolate.\nFinal distributive account filed\nby William Mlnning, executor .of\nwill of John Minni: g.\nInheritance tax determined in es\ntate of Charles E. Baker, no tax\ndue; Ida Hutchins, no tax due; and\nThomas Argue, $66.97. due.\nFirst partial account .filed by H\nWerner, Jr., administrator of es\ntate of Andrew Komisarz.\nAn order of appraisement of real\nestate issued to plaintiff in case of\nElle Cook, guardian vs Henry S\nSmith et al.\nLeiand E. Holzcr vs Clara G.\nFrazier, aid of execution.\nInheritance tax in estate of Fred\nerick Schi'linper certified to audi\ntor; amount, $603.34.\nMarriage Licenses\nWalter F. Price, 23, farmer, Sug\nar Ridge, and Leona Gokey, 22,\nbookkeeper. Bowling Green.\nLevi G. Davis, 26, piano tuner,\nButler Pa., and Helen Bayman, 22,\nwaitress, Fostoria, Wood Co.\nHenry Tegarden, 21,punchpress\noperator, Toledo, and Josephine\nChesley, 30, demonstrator, Bowling\nGreen.\nJohn Shaw, Jr., 23, car washer,\nBowling Green, and Babele Warner\n21, factory worker. Bowling Green.\nFrank T. Kirsch, 32, purchasing\nagent, Toledo, and Inez Best, 25,\nmanicurist. Bowling Green.\nJanies Rustage, 30. clerk. Por\ntage, and Elizabeth Hemphill, 22,\nbeautifician. Portage.\nRoland Gagnet, 23, tile setter,\nI Toledo, and Mat cel Dickson, 21,\nstenographer, Bowling Green.\nAndrew Deyoung, Jr., 21, glass\nworker, Rossford, and Shirley\nClark, 21, Rossford.\nCharles R. HanCe, 21, crane oper\nator, Lima, and Doris M. Wilson,\n19, factory worker, Perrysburg.\nRev. Carl Brown, 28. minister,\nBradner, and Florence Beard, 23.\nteacher, Perrysburg.\nAbaham Krabell, 26, driver, To\nledo, and Allyne Curre, 16, Ross\nford.\nHarry Allen, 22, pamller, Syl\nvania, and Elizabeth Haviland, 21,\nRossford.\nJohn Lambright, 27, laborer,\nBowling Green, and Mabel Crigger,\n26, factory worker, Johnstown, Pa.\nRobert Vincent, 20, inspector. To\nledo, and Elizabeth Loynes, 21, fac\ntory worker,* Rossford.\nHayden Coyer, 27, carpenter,\nBradner, and Bessie Spahn, 27,\nLuckey.\nRalph Huffine, 21, driver Cus\ntar, and Fairy Corfman, 23, Cus\ntar.\nJohnnie Wolff, 34, salesman, Cc\nlina, and Ruth D. Beaufore, 29,\nbeautician. Wood Co.\nGeo. A. Hillebrand, 34, tool\nmaker, Toledo, and Media Perry,\n26, Bowling Green.\nCOMMON PLEAS\nHarry E. Collin, et al, vs Thotaas\n,T. Kheoe, et al, lismissed without\nprejudice at plaintiff's costs.\nLouise Camper, et al, vs Caro\nline schurlg, et al, sale confirmed.\nIn matter of the sale of the Con\nservative U. B. church, sale con\nfirmed.\nClyde L. Bishop vs Harry G.\nShannon, passed out of assignment\nat defendant\u2019s costs.\nMrs. B. F. Blue vs Tno. Hoyman,\nleave to answer by May 3.\nChester Blue vs Jno. Hoyman,\nleave to answer by May 3.\nD. B. Bushey, as County Treas\nurer, vs Hiram W. Trout, finding\nfor plaintiff; lands ordered sold.\nTRANSFERS\nEthel M. Mercer to Donald R.\nMercer, lot 3326, Bo. Green, $1.\nJohn and Prudence Oates to\nClaude J. Murphy, 40 acres, Sect. 4\nHenry Twp. N. E. 40 acres. Sect.\n34, Liberty Twp; and 4 acres, Sect.\n33, same, $1.\nMrs. Roy and Roy Cline to Simon\nMatthias, lots 10 and 11, Bairds\ntown, $1.\nWilbert and Rhoda A. Bush to\nChas. J. Geidin, 5 acres. Sect. 33,\nPerrysburg Twp., $1.\nLouise Mueller to Arthur E. and\nChloe A. Leggett, lot 3670, Bowl\ning Green, $1.\nSarah S. and Franklin M. Car\nter to Geo. A. and Catherine T. J\nHoffman, 46 1-2 acres. Sect. 14\nPlain Twp., |1.\nHOYTVILLE CHICKS\ni make fine flock\nlWr. Chas. Werner .Deshler, Ohio,\nwrites as follows:\n\"We raised about 690 out of 715\nchicks. We had 362 pullets. I sold\nsome; have 242 with bands on. They\nbegan to lay last August the 25th.\nI did not give them laying mash\nuntil the last part of September.\nTheir production Is about 40 to 50\nper cent. Sure are laying fine. We\nsure hive a fine fl ;ck of pullets,\nLarge Leghorns and full of pep\u201d\nYou too wifi write a similarly en\nthusiastic letter after you have had\na shipment of Hoytville Accredited\nChicks. Get In touch with Hoytville\nAccredited Hatchery, Hiytvill'e, O.,\nor with one of its branch hatcheries\nat Weston Wayne or Bowling Green\nfor full information, prices and ca\ntalog. Hoytville Hatchery can also\nsupply you \"with high quality duck\nlings.\nOf especial interest to chick buy\ners Is the fact that every chick put'\nout from Hoytville or frrm one of\nthe branch hatcheries is Ohio Ac\ncredited which means that every\nbird has* been inspected and is up\nto standard requirements as to the\nbreed, type and egg prtducing abil\nity and has stood rigid inspection\nby an accredited judge. Accredited\nchicks make good records as pro\nducers for they have the breeding\nbehind them.\nHoytville Pekin Ducklings are aiso\nbecoming very popular, due to their\nrapid maturity. If you are interest\ned in having your brooder equip\nment do extra duty this season get\na shipment of Pekin Ducklings.\nSend $1.00 with order. Pay post\nman balance when Ducklings arrive.\n\"Now is the t'me to order May\nchicks. Reduced prices go into ef\nfect Thursday, May 8. You can get\nthese high quality accredited chicks\nat very favorable prices.\n\u2014Investigate\nMr. and Mrs. R. W. Pringle an i\nfamily spent Easter Sunday at To\nledo, at the home of her sister\nwhere a family birthday dinner was\ngiven in honor of Mrs. Pringle's\nnatal anniversary.\nW. A, Dresher and son Ralph,\nwere in Toledo on business last\nWednesday.\nO. H. Warner and family, spent j\nSunday in Perrysburg, guests hi\nEd Halbert and family.\nMiss Betty Fuller spent' Satur\nday and Sunday in the Fred Boul\nton home.\nFrank Miller spent the week end\nwith Junior Manor.\nEaster Sunday guests in the Roy\nHutchinspn \u2019home at Waterville\nwere, c._C. \u201cSpicer and family W. A.\nDrasclier and family, Elmer Hutch\ninson and Otto Falk.\nB. Q. and Bill Hawkins were in\nToledo, Tuesday.\nDon\u2019t forget the Legion dance at\n(he new Legion Hall Friday night,\nApril 25.\nMiss Margaret Conrad of Toledo,\n\u2022spent Easter with her parents.\nMrs. Ruth Thomas is visiting\nelatives In Toledo.\nMr. Clarence Freeworth was the\nEaster dinner, guest at the Jas. H.\nturwell home.\nMargaret Baker, who is attend\ning school at Columbus, spent Eas\nter at home, returning on Tuesday.\nMrs. Crosby and Mrs. Ex, called\non Mrs. Kate Dull who is stil very\npoorly. Mrs. Rose Fuller is caring\nfor her.\nMrs. Chas. Bowser and Carlon\nMiller of Toledo, .called on friends\nand relatives here, Sunday.\nMrs. i John Weaver and Sidney\nMalil were Bowling Green shoppers\non Saturday afternoon.\nSunday dinner guests at the W. i\nR. Lyle home were, Mr. and Mrs.\nFloyd Lyle and Jane of Holgate,\nand Mr. and Mrs. Don Kern and\nBillie.\ni i\nMr. and Mrs. Chas. Cox and Mar\ntha Chamberlin of Delta, and Dale\nWoodburn of Wanseon, ate Sunday\ndinner with Mr. and Mrs. Arthur\nWoodburn.\nMiss Maudie Tyner is making\nher home with Mr. and Mrs. John\nWeaver.\nW. H. Downing and family spent\nthe week end at Kunkie.\nMr. and Mrs. Lile Overly spent\nSunday with Mr. and Mrs. Fred\nOverly at Bryan.\nMr. and Mrs. James Guyer and\nMarjorie Lou of Findlay, and Mrs.\nCharles Bowser of Toledo, were\ncallers in the W. R. Dyle acme on\nSunday afternoon.\nElza Walters and family ate Sun\nday dinner with Mr. and Mrs. Sol\nomon Harmon near Napoleon, on\nthe river road.\nParent and Teachers meeting\nMay 5th.\nOn iHis Way Mere When Killed\nCharles E. Dennis, 53, Findlay\ncandy salesman, killed at Tontog\nany when struck by a fast B&O\npassenger train, was enroute to\nthis place to deliver candy to our\nlocal grocer, Mr. Fred Heeter.\nMisses Gladys and Helen Halbert\nof Perrysburg, were calling on\nfriends here on Friday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. B. C. Hawkins and\nson Dick and MI'S. Rose Fuller vis\nited* from Wednesday until Satur\nday with Mr. and Mrs. Harry Dick\nerson at Toledo.\nMr. and Mrs. F. I. Gam spent\nSunday with the former\u2019s mother,\nMrs. Fannie Gam, at Gibsonburg.\nAgnes Puls and Ruth Sanders\nattended Easter services at Custar\non Sunday morning.\nMrs. Angie McLain is not so well\nat this writing.\nMr. and Mrs. Pete Graf and Mrs.\nA. R. Tyner were shopping in To\nledo on Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Orta* Gallagher\nspent Easter with Mr. and Mrs.\nBernard Katon.\nDale Heyman and family and\nLillian Tyner spent Sunday after\nnoon with Jay Heyman\u2019s at Wes\nton.\nMr. and Mrs. Dale Overly are\nmoving into the Minnick property\non Second street.\nMrs. Otto Johnston of Cygnet,\nspent the day with Mrs. Lillian\nSeeley last Thursday.\nAlctd Seigneur Is out again after\nbeing confined to his home on ac\ncount of sickness.\nMerritt Smith is convalescing at\nhis home, having come from the\nhospital last Friday. Sunday callers\nwere: Mr. and Mrs. Ray Smith of\nFostoria, Mr. and Mrs. Bert Mc\nPherson, and Mr. and Mrs. Sam\nSmith of Bloomdale and Mr. and\nMrs. James Warner of McComb.\nMr. and Mrs. Louis Long and\nchildren of Toledo were Sunday\ncallers of Mr. and Mrs. Ed Oberle.\nMr. and Mrs. Clark Patton of\nBowling Green, entertained the\nRiver Bridge Club on Thursday\nevening.\nArthur Wade and family spent\nSunday with Geo. Weihl and wife\nof Weston.\nMr. and Mrs. J. E- Baldwin of\nToledo, spent Sunday with Ray\nmond Baldwin and family.\nFrank McCormick and family of\nSylvania spent Easter with G. Joy\nand family.\nDick Hollopeter and family of\nToledo spent Sunday with M. Fish\ner and family.\nMr. and Mrs. J. Kinder of Ham\nler spent Sunday with F. Allen and\nfamily.'\nThere will be regular preaching\nservices by Rev. Cordrey at 9:30\na. m. Sunday, followed by Sunday\nschool.\nThe Easter services last Sunday\nmorning were well attended. The\nEaster offering was given to the\nFlower Hospital, Toledo. Six babies\nwere baptized by Rev. Cordrey at\nthe church service.\nThe M. E. Ladies Aid Society de\nsire to thank those who patron\nized and contributed to their Ba\nzarr and Rake Sale last Saturday.\nPeter Shidler and family spent\nSunday with Forrest Russell and\nfamily of Findlay.\nClias. Kelly and family attended\na family reunion, Easter, at the\nhome of Mr. and Mrs. Sam Barton\nof Harrison Twp.\nPaul Vinuck and family and D.\nHuff and family of Toledo spent\nSunday with A. Haley and family.\nMrs. Noah Wells and son Omer,\nspent Easter with Burdette Wells\nand family of Fostoria.\nMisses Mary and Kathryn Carey\nRobert and Virgil Johnson, spent\nSunday afternoon in Toledo.\nMrs. Chas. Rice and son Ken\nneth and Miss Mollie Haley, spent\nMonday in Toledo.\nMr. and Mrs. F. Henry ot ham\nler, sent Thursday with F. Allen\nand tamlly.\nFrank Heeter and family of To\nledo, called on Mrs. Anna Sloan\nand Mr. and Mrs. Robert McKinley\non Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. L. A. Haley of To\nledo, spent Saturday at the A. Ha\nley home.\nR. Shaw and family of. Malihta,\nhave moved Into the I^wis Sloan\nresidence.\nMr. and Mrs. chas. Struble and\nMrs. E. Murrey of Wauseon, and\nMr. and Mrs. H. N. Murrey spent\nSunday with Mr. and Mrs. E. L\nEmery.\nMr and Mrs. G. H. Carey and R.\nGood and family, spent Sunday\nwith Ernest Grader and family near\nMallnta.\nMrs. E. Murrey and daughters of\nToledo, spent Friday with Mr. and\nMrs. H. N. Murrey.\nMr. and Mrs. LaPlante, Hazel and\nCarolus, and Worthy Owens, visit\ned in Liberty Center on Sunday\nafternoon.\nHarry Mason and daughter Mil\ndred and Mrs. Lucy Sprague of\nWeston were Friday evening dinner\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Lee Heyman\nand daughter Mae.\n(The following ladies from this\nplace attended the Pythian Sister\nInspection at the McClure Temple\non Wednesday night of last week:\nLillian Gray, Lydia Rice, Edith\nConn, Della Carey, Mollie Haley,\nGrace Allen, Nettie Hoff, Grace\nHowe, Rae Jones and Ida, Dorothy\nand Loretta plotts. On Friday night\nthe following ladies attended the\nPythian Sister Inspection at Ma\nlinta: Ella Creager, Golda Sprow,\nGail Conrad, Daza Audrey and Lo\nla Jones, Leona Shtdler, Edith Conn\nEdna Snively, Lydia Rice, Lillian\nGray, Nettie Hoff, Elizabeth and\nGrace Allen, Lura Hartman, Ida\nDorothy and Laretta Plotts, Mollie\nHaley, Rae Jones and Della Carey.\nThe ladies report a splendid time\nat both places.\nMr. and Mrs. B. C. Hawkins and\nDick, were Sunday dinner guests\nof Mr. and Mrs. Joe McKenzie.\nElza Walters and family were\ncallers in Napoleon, Friday after\nnoon. j ,-W\nMrs. Elza Tyner of Toledo spent\nEaster with her son, A. R. Tyner\nand family.\nMrs. Mabel Osterhout and Mr.\nCoharris of Toledo and Lawrence\nHuffman and family, were Sunday\ndinner guests in the Jay Huffman\nhome.\nClyde Bortel and Bob attended\nthe Toledo-St. Paul ball game at\nToledo on Saturday afternoon\nLulu Siders has returned to her\nwork at Milton Center, where she\nis employed by Mrs. Hathaway.\nParent and Teachers meeting\nMay 5th.\nNOTICE\u2014Please return milk bot\ntles! Tom Sterling\nInteresting:\nIf the figures prepared and an\nnounced by the Democratic state\nheadquarters in Columbus may be\nrelied upon:\u2014and thus far we have\nseen no positive denial\u2014Governor\nCopper is doing something in his\nown inimitable way to provide\nmore employment. Each week the\nDemocratic organization has been\ngiving out payroll figures for dif\nferent departments of the state\ngovernment, as they are being in\nvestigated\u2014It is mighty fine, of\ncourse, to be giving employment to\nmore people in these days of indus\ntrial depression, when so many of\nour factory workers are idle, or are\nworking but part time. The Govern\nor has been talking at great length\nabout the return of prosperity and\nsome commission oi committee has\nbeen working on the problem. The\nstate shows how ii can be done by\nemploying many more workers\u2014at\nthe expense of the already over\nburdened taxpayers Unfortunately,\nthe man out of a job, and who is\nwondering how he can get enough\nmoney to pay the taxes on his little\nhome, will not wax very enthusias\ntic over this kind of prosperity. Lf\nThe politicians surrounding the\nGovernor are not worrying, how\never, they are taking good care to\nsee that the new jobs and increased\npay go to the right men. The \u201cpay-\nroll boys\u201d.'thelr tribe now Increas\ning, are counted upon to whoop it\nup for a second term for the Gov\nernor, and also for the nomination\nof Senator McCulloch to succeed\nhimself. Jones, the taxpayer, \"pays\nthe- freight.\u201d\n\u2014Sandusky Journal\nUNDERGOES OPERATION\nMrs. Frank Sheats, who under\nwent an operation on Monday p. m.\nat her home at this place, for. gaH\nstones and peritonitis, is doing as\nwell as could be expected.\nThe operation was performed by\nDr. Bidwell of St. Vincent\u2019s Hos\nWetherill\npltal, assisted by Dr. Johnston, of\nTontogany and Dr. Wetheriil Of\nWeston.\nDROWNED MAX NOT FOUND\nI\nThe body of Michael Gels, 11, of\nHaskins, who was drowned late\nTuesday at Indlanola island, mas\nnot been found as we go to press.\nGels and four companions who\nwere employed on a construction\njob at the island, were crossing to\nthe mainland when their boat cap*\nsized, throwing them into the river.\nThey all succeeded in seizing a ca-\nble suspended from the island ex*\neept Gels, who sank out of sight.'\nHis companions attempted to res*\n'iie him but failed. Repeated diving\nand crews with grappling hooks\nhave labored thus far, in vain.\nReturns Without Body 1\nFuneral director Fred Gill drove\nthe ambulance to Columbus on\nTuesday morning with the expefc*\ntation of bringing back the body\nof Pearl Kreager of Napoleon, one\nof the unfortunates to die in the\npenitentiary fire, but was informed\nthat no bodies would be released\nbefore Wednesday afternoon, and\nthat the body would be dressed for\nburial and casket and transporta\ntion charges would be prepaid to\ntheir destination.\nThe body will arrive at Liberty\nCenter on Friday at 8:15 a. m.,\nand from there to Napoleon.\nLatest reports from Mrs. Grant\nWeldon, who underwent an opera\ntion at the Woman\u2019s and Children\u2019s\u2019\nHospital, Toledo, are that she Is\nrecovering nicely.\nNICKEL PLATE TIME TABLE\nStandard Time\nEast Bound\nNo. 16 6:01 a. m.\nNo. 14 6:14 p. m.\n-K\n7:01 a. m.\n7:10 p. m.^-\nWest Bound\nNo. 13\nNo. 15\n.-\u2022A*\nfarm-to-Market Roads\nAn Economic Necessity\nStatisticians tell us that our total\nnational income, that is to say, the\nincome of all the people in the\nUnited States, approximates ninety\nbillions of dollars each year. Out\nof that immense total, the people\nof the United States spent one and\none-half billion dollars for road\nbuilding in 1929. During the pres\nent year it is estimated that not\nless than two billion dollars will be\nexpended for this same purpose.\nIn view of the many billions of\ndollars that have been spent on\nour roads during the past decade,\nthe existing mileage of unimproved\nroads is rather startling. Of the\n3,000,000 miles of rural roads in\nthe United States, approximately\n2,500,000 are still dirt roads. And\nof the 6,250,000 farms in this great\ncountry of ours, nearly 5,000,000\nare located on these same dirt\nroads.\nExpenditures for Roads\nWe spent approximately 370 mil\nlion dollars to build the Panama\nCanal. Every three months we\nspend the price of the Panama\nCanal on our roads, and yet only{\nfive per cent of our farms are\nserved by year-round surfaced\nroads.\nThe situation in Ohio is of\nespecial interest to us. From the:\ngasoline tax alone, the state of\nOhio has collected $101,000,000.\nsince the first gas tax law became\neffective in April, 1925. Yet Ohio\n.has 39,000 miles of dirt roads, and!\nthere are 90,000 farms located on J\nthese dirt roads.\nIt can hardly be denied that in!\nOhio, as in the United States as a'\nwhole, our road building program\nhas signally failed to serve agricul\nture.\nDistribution of Farm Produce\nThere has been much discussion\nof farm relief, and some legisla\ntion has been enacted designed to\nrescue the farmer from his plight.\nNearly all of this discussion has\ncentered about one major topic, the I\nmarketing of farm products. For\nwhile agriculture has kept pace]\nwith geheral industrial progress j\nInsofar as the processes of produc-1\ntion are concerned, this has not\nbeen true of the distribution of\nfarm products.\nDirt roads often compel the far\nmer to market his crops not when\nhe chooses, but when he can\u2014-dur\ning the few weeks when his dirt\nroad is dry and hard. A market\nglut follows, Whereas a year-round\nroad would have enabled him to\navoid this seasonal glut.\nThis is but a single illustration\nof the fact that whereas our eco\nnomic system is geared to rapid\nV* transportation, the distribution of*\nI our agricultural produce depend!\ntoo often upon the same methods\nemployed a century ago. We have\nmotorized transport in almost\nevery industry except agriculture.\nAnd to tiic farmer we have said:\n,-\u201cBe patient until the main routes\n\u2018are paved, then your farm roads\nshall have our attention.\u201d\n\u2022.Ti\nrs\nWill the Farmer Ever Reach the\nPromised Land?\nToday wo say to him: \"Now that\nthese main State highways are\npaved, they need to be widened\nand straightened and otherwise\nimproved, so that motorists may\ntravel ever them at 60 miles an\nhour, and so that the highways\nmay carry loads which used to be\nborne on steel rails.\u201d\nHence today the farmer still\nawaits the promised aid in taking\nhim out of the mud. From afar\nhe sees the promised land; it is\nnot for him, but possibly for his\nchildren\u2019s children, to enter it.\nIt is quite popular today to ad\nmit that low-cost farm-to-market\nroads arc a national economic nec\nessity, but there is slight effort on\nthe part of highway engineers to\nhasten the dawn of the new day.\nToo often these officials prefer to\ntear up nnd replace roads which\ncouid have been improved and\ntransformed into strong, durable\npavements at a fraction of the\ncost of replacing them.\n4\nWasteful Methods in Road Building\nIt cannot be denied thit in the\npast a considerable pari of bur\nroad building expenditures have\nbeen wasteful. Too little effort has\nbeen given to securing a large\nmileage of low cost roads. Too\nlittle attention has been given to\nthe use of local materials, to intel\nligent maintenance and surface\ntreatments. In many cases expen\nsive pavements have been con\nstructed where a surfacing cost\ning less than one-third the amount\nwould have furnished adequate\n\n:3\nservice.\nWe sacrifice our investment In\nexisting foundations and materials\njust as recklessly as we sacrifice\nhuman lives in our mania foije\nspeed, and for more speed. Thirty\nthousand fatalities a year in auto\nmobile accidents no longer appall\nus. Two billion dollars a year for\nroad construction hardly startles\nus.\n_ Meantime, the farmer will con\ntinue to suffer from the same lack\nof transport facilities as in the\npast. For it is an old adage that\nyqu cannot eat your cake and have\nit too. You cannot make much\nprogress toward improving the\n2,500,000 miles of farmers\u2019 roads\nuntil there is less waste and de- _\nstruction of existing foundation,'\nmaterials on the 500,000 miles of\nmain highways.\n\n-M\nV","height":"29516","width":"21436"}}
